1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,840
Stan got eight hours last night, a full eight.

2
00:00:03,840 --> 00:00:06,760
In bed on time, no coffee afternoon.

3
00:00:06,760 --> 00:00:09,040
He did everything the internet told him to,

4
00:00:09,040 --> 00:00:13,160
and right now, at three in the afternoon, he is a zombie.

5
00:00:13,160 --> 00:00:15,520
Eyes heavy, brain static.

6
00:00:15,520 --> 00:00:18,600
He could put his head on the desk and be out in four seconds.

7
00:00:18,600 --> 00:00:21,680
So tonight, he'll go to bed early and fix it.

8
00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:26,440
And at 11 p.m., he's wide awake, wired, scrolling,

9
00:00:26,440 --> 00:00:31,520
suddenly full of energy and big ideas at exactly the wrong time.

10
00:00:31,520 --> 00:00:35,880
Tired all day, awake all night, eight hours of sleep,

11
00:00:35,880 --> 00:00:38,360
and he still feels like he's running on three.

12
00:00:38,360 --> 00:00:39,840
Here's the strange part.

13
00:00:39,840 --> 00:00:42,480
The problem usually isn't how much you slept.

14
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:44,240
You could fix the sleep completely

15
00:00:44,240 --> 00:00:46,360
and still feel exactly like this.

16
00:00:46,360 --> 00:00:49,960
Because being tired all the time isn't really about sleep at all.

17
00:00:49,960 --> 00:00:52,920
It's about something most of us were never told we have.

18
00:00:52,920 --> 00:00:55,640
And once you see it, this whole exhausting loop

19
00:00:55,640 --> 00:00:57,720
finally makes sense.

20
00:00:57,720 --> 00:01:00,440
The obvious answer is, just sleep more.

21
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:04,440
And for some people, sure, they're genuinely short on hours.

22
00:01:04,440 --> 00:01:06,360
But you know people who are not.

23
00:01:06,360 --> 00:01:08,600
People who get their eight, nine, 10 hours

24
00:01:08,600 --> 00:01:11,440
and still drag through the afternoon like Stan.

25
00:01:11,440 --> 00:01:13,720
If tiredness were only about quantity,

26
00:01:13,720 --> 00:01:15,720
more sleep would fix everyone.

27
00:01:15,720 --> 00:01:16,560
It doesn't.

28
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:18,520
So if it's not the amount, what is it?

29
00:01:18,520 --> 00:01:19,880
Here's what nobody mentions.

30
00:01:19,880 --> 00:01:22,080
You don't have one system keeping you awake.

31
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:23,280
You have two.

32
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:25,280
And they do not always agree.

33
00:01:25,320 --> 00:01:27,760
The first one you already feel.

34
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:30,840
The longer you're awake, the more tired you get.

35
00:01:30,840 --> 00:01:33,440
Scientists call it sleep pressure.

36
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:35,440
All day, your brain burns fuel

37
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:39,080
and a molecule called adenosine slowly builds up.

38
00:01:39,080 --> 00:01:42,760
The more it piles up, the heavier your eyelids feel.

39
00:01:42,760 --> 00:01:46,720
Picture sand trickling into an hourglass all day.

40
00:01:46,720 --> 00:01:48,800
By night, the glass is full.

41
00:01:48,800 --> 00:01:51,360
Sleep flips it over and empties it.

42
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:55,240
That's why you wake up clear and fade as the hours go on.

43
00:01:55,240 --> 00:01:58,960
And coffee, caffeine doesn't remove the sand.

44
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:01,760
It just tapes over the sensor that reads it.

45
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:03,400
The pile is still there.

46
00:02:03,400 --> 00:02:04,840
You've simply stopped feeling it

47
00:02:04,840 --> 00:02:06,800
until the caffeine wears off

48
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:09,000
and it all crashes back at once.

49
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,720
So that's clock number one.

50
00:02:11,720 --> 00:02:13,720
Pressure that builds while you're up

51
00:02:13,720 --> 00:02:15,440
and drains while you sleep.

52
00:02:15,440 --> 00:02:17,880
But here's the part that changes everything.

53
00:02:17,880 --> 00:02:19,440
There is a second clock

54
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:21,880
and it does not care how long you've been awake.

55
00:02:21,880 --> 00:02:24,240
Deep in your brain behind your eyes

56
00:02:24,240 --> 00:02:27,200
sits a cluster of about 20,000 cells,

57
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:29,080
smaller than a grain of rice.

58
00:02:29,080 --> 00:02:32,800
And it is the master clock for your entire body.

59
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:35,400
It runs a roughly 24 hour cycle

60
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:37,160
and it decides when you feel sharp

61
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:40,480
and when you feel wiped, no matter how much you slept.

62
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:43,520
And it keeps a schedule, a real one.

63
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:46,520
Late morning, it pushes you to a peak.

64
00:02:46,520 --> 00:02:48,280
You're at your sharpest.

65
00:02:48,280 --> 00:02:50,520
Then around two to four in the afternoon,

66
00:02:50,520 --> 00:02:52,000
it does the opposite.

67
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,440
It dips hard.

68
00:02:54,440 --> 00:02:58,440
That mid afternoon wall where your brain turns to soup,

69
00:02:58,440 --> 00:03:00,000
that is not your lunch.

70
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:03,360
That is your clock dimming the lights on purpose.

71
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:06,320
People who skip lunch feel the exact same dip

72
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:08,440
at the exact same time.

73
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:11,400
And then at night, right when you're trying to wind down,

74
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:13,480
it can do something almost cruel.

75
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:16,560
It hands you a second wind, a burst of energy

76
00:03:16,560 --> 00:03:17,920
right before bed.

77
00:03:17,920 --> 00:03:19,440
That is not random.

78
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:21,280
Your clock has a window in the evening

79
00:03:21,280 --> 00:03:23,440
where it actively fights off sleep.

80
00:03:23,440 --> 00:03:25,080
And if you push your bedtime into it,

81
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:27,040
you will lie there wide awake,

82
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:29,520
just like Stan at 11 p.m.

83
00:03:29,520 --> 00:03:32,560
So look at Stan's whole day again.

84
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:35,440
The afternoon crash, the midnight energy.

85
00:03:35,440 --> 00:03:36,960
None of it was random.

86
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:39,880
He was just reading a schedule he didn't know he had.

87
00:03:39,880 --> 00:03:42,160
So what sets this clock?

88
00:03:42,160 --> 00:03:45,280
What tells those cells what time it actually is?

89
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:47,720
Light, almost entirely light.

90
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:49,520
Inside your eyes are special cells

91
00:03:49,520 --> 00:03:51,640
that have nothing to do with seeing.

92
00:03:51,640 --> 00:03:53,400
Their only job is to measure light

93
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:55,760
and report it straight to the master clock.

94
00:03:55,760 --> 00:03:58,120
Bright light in the morning tells the clock,

95
00:03:58,120 --> 00:04:00,720
it's daytime, start the day,

96
00:04:00,720 --> 00:04:03,040
and locks the whole schedule into place.

97
00:04:03,040 --> 00:04:05,240
But light at night does the reverse.

98
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:09,000
It says, it's still daytime, stay up,

99
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
and shoves the schedule later.

100
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,800
And blue light is the strongest signal of all.

101
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:16,600
The cool, bright glow pouring out of your phone,

102
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:18,600
your laptop, your TV.

103
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:20,440
It suppresses melatonin,

104
00:04:20,440 --> 00:04:22,480
the hormone meant to make you sleepy,

105
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:24,680
and nudges your clock backward.

106
00:04:24,680 --> 00:04:28,560
So when Stan lies in bed scrolling to relax,

107
00:04:28,560 --> 00:04:30,240
he is not relaxing.

108
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:33,520
He is holding a tiny sun a few inches from his face,

109
00:04:33,520 --> 00:04:36,040
telling his clock the day isn't over.

110
00:04:36,040 --> 00:04:39,280
Night after night, pushing his own bedtime later,

111
00:04:39,280 --> 00:04:42,000
then blaming himself for not being tired.

112
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,680
And this is where it all comes together.

113
00:04:44,680 --> 00:04:48,200
The real reason so many of us feel tired all the time.

114
00:04:48,200 --> 00:04:50,200
It's not that you aren't sleeping.

115
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:51,720
It's that your clock and your life

116
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:54,040
are set to two different time zones.

117
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:56,240
Scientists even have a name for it.

118
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:58,080
Social jet lag.

119
00:04:58,080 --> 00:05:01,120
Think about your week, Monday through Friday,

120
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:04,560
and alarm rips you out of sleep before your body is ready.

121
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:06,320
Your clock wanted more.

122
00:05:06,320 --> 00:05:08,080
The alarm did not care.

123
00:05:08,080 --> 00:05:11,040
Then the weekend arrives, no alarm.

124
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:13,440
So you sleep in.

125
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:16,120
Your body finally gets to run on its own schedule,

126
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:17,640
drifting later.

127
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:20,200
And then Monday slams the alarm back down.

128
00:05:20,200 --> 00:05:23,240
Hours earlier than your body has now drifted to.

129
00:05:23,240 --> 00:05:26,120
You didn't fly anywhere, but your body did.

130
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:28,280
Every single weekend, you give yourself

131
00:05:28,280 --> 00:05:30,280
a tiny dose of jet lag.

132
00:05:30,280 --> 00:05:33,480
Flying west on Saturday, flying east on Monday,

133
00:05:33,480 --> 00:05:35,760
then spending the whole week with that groggy,

134
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:39,320
wrung out what time zone am I even in feeling?

135
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:42,840
Because biologically, that is exactly what you are.

136
00:05:42,840 --> 00:05:44,280
Jet lagged.

137
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:47,600
You just never left your house, and this is not rare.

138
00:05:47,640 --> 00:05:50,400
In large studies, more than two out of three people

139
00:05:50,400 --> 00:05:53,000
carry at least an hour of this misalignment,

140
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:54,560
every single week.

141
00:05:54,560 --> 00:05:56,400
Plenty are carrying two or three,

142
00:05:56,400 --> 00:05:58,560
the equivalent of flying across the country

143
00:05:58,560 --> 00:06:00,640
and back over and over.

144
00:06:00,640 --> 00:06:03,320
So if you feel tired all the time,

145
00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:05,400
here's the part worth hearing.

146
00:06:05,400 --> 00:06:07,040
You are probably not lazy.

147
00:06:07,040 --> 00:06:09,120
You are almost certainly not broken.

148
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:10,560
You are out of sync.

149
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:12,720
Your body is keeping perfect time.

150
00:06:12,720 --> 00:06:14,680
It is just keeping it for a different schedule

151
00:06:14,680 --> 00:06:17,200
than the one your life is forcing on it.

152
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:19,600
And here's the strangest twist of all.

153
00:06:19,600 --> 00:06:22,680
Even the thing we call normal sleep,

154
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:27,200
one long, unbroken block, turns out to be surprisingly new.

155
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:31,280
For most of human history, people did not sleep that way at all.

156
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:34,880
Historians digging through old diaries, court records,

157
00:06:34,880 --> 00:06:37,360
even lines from Homer and Virgil,

158
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:40,920
kept finding the same pattern over and over.

159
00:06:40,920 --> 00:06:44,160
People had a first sleep and a second sleep.

160
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:46,800
They would go down a couple of hours after dark,

161
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:50,800
then wake up around midnight on purpose for an hour or two.

162
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:52,480
And they used that time.

163
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:54,640
They prayed, tended the fire,

164
00:06:54,640 --> 00:06:56,920
talked to whoever was beside them,

165
00:06:56,920 --> 00:06:59,000
even visited the neighbors.

166
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,080
Then went down for their second sleep until dawn.

167
00:07:02,080 --> 00:07:05,560
Waking up in the dead of night wasn't a problem to be fixed.

168
00:07:05,560 --> 00:07:08,600
It was just the natural seam in the middle of the night.

169
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:12,520
Then came artificial light, first lamps, then the light bulb.

170
00:07:12,520 --> 00:07:13,840
We pushed our evenings later,

171
00:07:13,840 --> 00:07:16,560
squeezed sleep into one tight block,

172
00:07:16,560 --> 00:07:19,240
and quietly forgot the gap had ever been there.

173
00:07:19,240 --> 00:07:23,080
Now, historians still argue about how widespread this really was,

174
00:07:23,080 --> 00:07:25,120
so we shouldn't oversell it.

175
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:28,920
But it raises a genuinely comforting thought.

176
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:31,680
If you wake at 3 a.m., and lie there,

177
00:07:31,680 --> 00:07:32,920
calm but alert,

178
00:07:32,920 --> 00:07:36,680
convinced something is wrong with you, maybe nothing is.

179
00:07:36,680 --> 00:07:39,840
Maybe you are just running an older version of the program.

180
00:07:39,840 --> 00:07:43,640
The one your great, great grandparents would have recognized in a heartbeat.

181
00:07:43,640 --> 00:07:46,200
So, why are you tired all the time?

182
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:49,000
Usually it's not because you are failing at sleep.

183
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,280
It's because you've got a 24 hour body

184
00:07:51,280 --> 00:07:54,200
trying to run on a 9 to 5 world's clock.

185
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:55,960
Two timers that don't agree.

186
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:58,040
A master clock set by light,

187
00:07:58,040 --> 00:08:00,200
and a schedule built for a spinning planet,

188
00:08:00,200 --> 00:08:02,040
not a calendar app.

189
00:08:02,040 --> 00:08:03,960
Now, one honest note,

190
00:08:03,960 --> 00:08:07,040
real exhaustion that drags on for weeks and never lifts

191
00:08:07,040 --> 00:08:09,280
can sometimes be something medical.

192
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:13,360
A thyroid running slow, low iron sleep apnea.

193
00:08:13,400 --> 00:08:16,280
That's a quick visit to a doctor, not a video,

194
00:08:16,280 --> 00:08:18,680
but that every day foggy,

195
00:08:18,680 --> 00:08:21,720
why am I always like this kind of tired?

196
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:24,320
That one is very often just timing.

197
00:08:24,320 --> 00:08:26,040
You are not a tired person,

198
00:08:26,040 --> 00:08:28,000
you are a perfectly good clock,

199
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,400
being asked to keep the wrong time.

200
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:33,400
And the next time you find yourself wide awake at midnight,

201
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:35,880
buzzing with energy you can't use,

202
00:08:35,880 --> 00:08:38,360
you can at least smile about one thing.

203
00:08:38,360 --> 00:08:40,160
A few hundred years ago,

204
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:42,200
that wasn't a problem at all.

205
00:08:42,200 --> 00:08:44,440
That was simply called being awake

206
00:08:44,440 --> 00:08:45,960
between your two sleeps.

